 High German <i>bracke</i>.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>brake</i> ‘brushwood’, also ‘breach point in the dyke’, or a habitational name from any of the places called Braack and Brake in northern Germany.","Swiss German: nickname for a slow or clumsy person."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Johanna Cantilupe Breasey was born in 1172, in Winwick, Northamptonshire, England. She married Sir, Thomas Andrews , II, Knight in 1193, in Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1194, in her hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1172–1194":"1172–1194","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1200":"1200","1163":"1163","1172":"1172","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1172–1194":"1172–1194","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1194–Male":"1194–Kuollut","1200":"1200","1163":"1163","1172":"1172","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1172–1194":"1172–1194","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1194–Male":"1194–Décédé","1200":"1200","1163":"1163","1172":"1172","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Angleterre","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lady Johanna Cantilupe Breasey est née en 1172, à Winwick, Northamptonshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Sir, Thomas Andrews , II, Knight en 1193, à Northamptonshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1194, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 22 ans."},"de":{"1172–1194":"1172–1194","1163–1200":"1163–1200","1194–Male":"1194–Verstorben","1200":"1200","1163":"1163","1172":"1172","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England","lifeSummary":"Lady Johanna Cantilupe Breasey wurde 1172 in Winwick, Northamptonshire, England geboren. Sie hat 1193 in Northamptonshire, England Sir, Thomas Andrews , II, Knight geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn. Sie starb 1194 im Alter von 22 J